My Review:
After reading "The Book of Why", I was looking for a more technical introduction to causality. Since by background in machine learning using kernel methods, this book co-authored by Bernhard Schölkopf seemed a good start.

Though I skimmed through the latter chapters, the beginning gives a good introduction to the different types of causality and which assumptions that have to be made. I especially liked the chapters drawing links between causality and topics like transfer learning and domain adaptation!

Also, I agree with many other reviewers that the constant name dropping is a bit annoying.

Title: Scale: The Universal Laws of Growth, Innovation, Sustainability, and the Pace of Life in Organisms, Cities, Economies, and Companies
Author: Geoffrey B. West
My Review:
A very interesting read! In my courses on ecology and human nutrition we have used some of the scaling laws and I always found them intriguing. Only when reading this book I feel that I understand how these laws arise. West does a good job relating diverse properties of organisms, companies and cities to their sizes. When physicists talk about biology I am always sceptical. Luckily, West is only condescending in about 10% of the times (seriously, finding it unimaginable that the great progresses of biology in the 20th century are at the same level as the increase in understanding of physics show a certain lack of respect for other fields).

Nevertheless, the ideas of this book will surely stay with you.

Pet peeve: why do all plots have slightly different layouts?

Title: Things to Make and Do in the Fourth Dimension
Author: Matt    Parker
My Review:
There seem to be fewer good popular mathematics books than, say, popular physics books. This book covers a whole range of mathematical topics, not because of their applications, but because math is fun! Parker covers things from exotic ways of cutting pizzas to making a computer from domino bricks. His enthusiasm is contagious and he always gives you the impression that you could have come up with these things yourself.

A very recommended read for everybody who enjoyed math in high school and university.

Title: The Circle
Author: Dave Eggers
My Review:
The Circle is the largest internet company in the world. Almost everyone uses their search engine, social media, payment system... The Circle's mission is to make all information always available for everyone.

In this novel we follow Mae, a young ambitious graduates who lands her dream job in the Circle in customer services. Employees are expected participate in the companies social media as much as possible and generally contribute as much information and data as possible, in the interest of the community company's functioning and their own well being. After all, secrets are lies and sharing is caring.

Though the story is quite simple, the satire is quite topical and the book is worth a read.

My Review:
After failing to get past this page 15o more than ten years ago, I gave this book another go. The first 40 pages (in the Shire) were quite enjoyable, though the next part, Frodo, Sam, Merrin and Peppin's journey was quite dull. Only when they finally decided what to do with the titular artefact of doom the story really takes off and becomes the epic quest for which it is famous.

Though I appreciate the world building of Tolkin, I find the characterisation to be somewhat lacking compared to other (modern?) fantasy stories.

Title: Harry Potter and the Cursed Child: Parts One and Two (Harry Potter, #8)
Author: John Tiffany
My Review:
Got it today and finished it a couple of hours later. As I foolishly pre-ordered it instead of buying it in the bookstore, I was already spoiled by some hard-to-miss reviews, both abut the quality as well as some plot points.

Being quite the former (okay, not that 'former') Potter geek I really wanted it to be good. The new material on Pottermore has made me somewhat cautious not to hold too great expectations. Though Rowling is clearly enjoying herself making new material (and still has lot's of love for her series), she seems do it for 'fun' rather than really bring something novel to the Potterverse.

Obviously, I enjoyed reading it. The script form does IMO not deviate too much from the often dialogue-oriented original series, and the descriptions about how the characters nonverbally react convey a surprisingly large amount of emotions. Sometimes it really feels good to be able to binge a whole story in a couple of hours.


Sadly, there are quite a lot of issues with the plots that are lacking - to put it mildly. People more adept in reviewing than me have given a more comprehensive list that me, but some things I really did not like:
- Time traveling? teminator-style trolley lady? Voldemort and Bellatrix' daughter? Stuff bad fanfics are made of...
- Poor professor McGonagall: after defending Harry multiple times against the ministry and death eaters she is being blackmailed by the very boy she tried to protect into acting as Umbridge...
- Cedric becoming a death eater after loosing the Triwizard Tournament?!
- Ron is apparently a loser in any time line. Seriously, in the books he was quite a nice and intelligent guy, here he only serves to make Harry and Hermione look good.
- Bitter teacher Hermione.
- Resistance Hermione with attraction to Snape...


Fans read it, but do not necessarily consider it canon, because not everything is to like.


As a small side note, it side with the voices to make Albus and Scorpio a couple. There is an amazing chemistry between these boys. Why not give the word a real gay pairing (other than an asexual 100 year old...)? They could do it for the Legend of Korra, why can't Rowling gives us a same sex pairing? The retconned Hermione to be black (which I very much applaud!), why not show the world it is ok to be gay?

Title: The Sketchnote Handbook: The Illustrated Guide to Visual Note Taking
Author: Mike Rohde
My Review: The what, why and how of sketchnotes : summarizing meetings and presentations using an entertaining combination of text and hand drawn images. Looking forward to my next conference!

Title: Lolito
Author: Ben Brooks
My Review:
So ok, it's average?

Lolito is about a bored, depressed teen sitting home alone. It's funny, but not hilarious. There is inappropriate sex, but it is not scandalous. It is just a book you enjoy reading, but are not particularly rememberable.

Title: The Vegetarian Flavor Bible: The Essential Guide to Culinary Creativity with Vegetables, Fruits, Grains, Legumes, Nuts, Seeds, and More, Based on the Wisdom of Leading American Chefs
Author: Karen Page

Title: Geroezemoes in het gras
Author: Dave Goulson
My Review: Terrific book about the nature in our backyards. Goulson explains how everything insect and plant is connected in an ecological web - and why it is vital to conserve it.

Title: Phage
Author: Mark Tamplin
My Review:
Phage is a scientific thriller. The main character is a professor in microbiology who uses phages (viruses of bacteria) to stop epidemics. An unstable scientist is planning a nation-wide bioterrorism attack. A race against the clock ensures where multiple parties try to stop him. Think Dan Brown with microbiology instead of history.

It was clear to me that this is the first work of Tamplin, sometimes the dialogues and characters seem a bit artificial. Nevertheless, I very much enjoyed reading this novel. The plot was fast-paced and the prose was agreeable. I liked that that the author sometimes 'zooms in' to some of the event in the micro-world (in the first pages describing the conjugation of bacteria that have lead to virulence, details of the PCR reaction...). Since I enjoy reading populair science, I would ready stuff like that even undiluted, though I can imagine some people to be turned off by 'a biology lecture'.

If there would be a sequel, I would gladly read it.

Title: The Book of Strange New Things
Author: Michel Faber
My Review: A very personal story about faith and love disguised as a science-fiction/dystopian novel.

Title: The Call of Cthulhu and Other Weird Stories
Author: H.P. Lovecraft

Title: Fluwelen Begeerte
Author: Sarah Waters
My Review: Being a lesbien in the Victorian age. Very pleasantly written, but a bit of a dull story.

Title: Drifting on Alien Winds: Exploring the Skies and Weather of Other Worlds
Author: Michael            Carroll

Title: Consciousness Explained
Author: Daniel C. Dennett
My Review:
A 400+ pages book that tries to combine philosophy, neuroscience, psychology, evolution, AI research.. into a coherent theory of consciousness. Does Dennett succeed? In my opinion not, but he is in good company of other thinkers who tried.

Dennett's main thesis is that there is little viewer in our head who processes all the information linearly (the so-called an appalled 'Cartesian theatre'). Instead Dennett argues for a multiple draft model which states that there is no stream of conscious experience. Like Hofstadter consciousness is assumed to be an emergent property of a system being able to be introspective.

This is a heavy book, crammed with a lot of ideas (some of them not easy to follow). A lot of it is really enjoyable to read, but a definite theory of the mind? I think not.

Title: I, Robot (Robot, #0.1)
Author: Isaac Asimov
My Review:
First time I have read work from Asimov. Each chapter is a short-story framed by an interview with a retiring robot-psychologist. Every story is a case of a rogue or malfunctioning robot that the employees of US Robots have to investigate using their wits and the knowledge that all robots have to follow the three laws of robotics:

1) don't injure humans and protect them from harm
2) always follow human orders (except if in conflict with law 1)
3) protect yourself (except if in conflict with the above laws)

Given that we are slowly entering the world which Asimov has envisioned (the self-driving cars are slowly upon us), this book and its philosophical musings are now perhaps more relevant than 60 years ago.

Title: Mannen zonder vrouw
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review: Though for some reason I cannot bring myself to like Murakami as much as I used to - his writing style and topics get a bit old after some books, I still enjoyed reading this one. It is a collection of short-stories, each with a different male protagonist who has recently lost a woman in his life. The stories range from quite straightforward to peculiar to more full-blown magic realism. Definitely worthwhile to read a story before going to bed!

Title: Calamity (The Reckoners, #3)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: I really enjoyed this series as a whole. It was simple, funny, action-packed and overall a delightful read. Sanderson explores the superhero genre similar to what Watchmen did some years earlier. Rather than focussing on how society would react to 'costumed vigilantes', Sanderson has Geeky fun exploring and discussing the limits and loopholes of the various powers. Though the characters are rather forgettable and the ending seems a bit rushed, there are far worse ways to waste some afternoons than the Reckoners.

Title: Daar is hij weer
Author: Timur Vermes
My Review: Adolf Hitler is back in the present day and everybody is kinda ok with it. Amusing an well-researched, but lacking a bit of depth.

Title: What Is Life?: How Chemistry Becomes Biology
Author: Addy Pross
My Review:
Countless excellent books on evolution have described how life could adapt and become more complex based on Darlings natural selection. Many of these books omit the origin of life.

This book tries to bridge chemistry and biology via systems chemistry to obtain a coherent theory of life. Though technical details are somewhat lacking, the author is able to bring his point across quite lucidly. He presents a framework in which chemical and biological evolution are treated as the same through the term dynamic kinetic stability. This reminds me of the construction theory, another scientific theory for the origin of patterns and life, though this book is much better at representing its ideas.

A short and enjoyable read with a couple of interesting ideas.

Title: The Monocle Guide to Better Living
Author: Monocle

Author: Stuart A. Kauffman

Title: The Art of Fermentation: An in-Depth Exploration of Essential Concepts and Processes from Around the World
Author: Sandor Ellix Katz

Title: Systems and Synthetic Biology
Author: Vikram Singh
My Review:
Systems biology is the science of understanding living systems as a whole and synthetic biology is the science of making new organisms or components of organisms. Interesting these topics may be, this remains a paper book, hence the quality and cohesion varies enormously from chapter to chapter.

I got this book for free for performing a review, useful for getting an overview of the current hot topics and literature, but it fails to be a global reference for the topics.

Title: De man die de taal van de slangen sprak
Author: Andrus Kivirähk
My Review: One of the best books that I have read this year.

Title: Junk DNA: A Journey Through the Dark Matter of the Genome
Author: Nessa Carey
My Review: Leaving the hard core genetics and molecular biology field in favor for computer science, I was nearly forgotten how fascinating the living cell can be. Carey sketches the clockwork of living beings, painting the proteins as merely the dumb muscle and DNA and RNA the true main actors.

Title: IPython Interactive Computing and Visualization Cookbook
Author: Cyrille Rossant
My Review: Good reference for common scientific python problems.

Title: The Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction
Author: Trevor Hastie

Title: Skin Deep (Legion, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Nice read. Should indeed be a good basis for an excellent TV show!

Title: Our Mathematical Universe: My Quest for the Ultimate Nature of Reality
Author: Max Tegmark
My Review: Telmark gives an (highly individualized) overview of all of physics to come to his main conclusion: the universe is a mathematical structure. Personally, I find it strange that this should be controversial, I always thought it was math 'all the way down'. The writing style is quite enjoyable and the anecdotes are relevant. Recommended if recreational physics is your cup of tea.

Title: Lelieblank, scharlaken rood
Author: Michel Faber
My Review:
This is a though one to rate. On the one hand, Faber writes in a beautiful style and for a 950-ish book, it is quite a page turner. On the other hand, it is a dull, long story filled with unlikeable characters. As some other reviewers noted, for a book that is mainly written from the point of view of a strong-willed and intelligent prostitute, it is quite misogynistic. A friend of me remarked that I likely does not pass the Bechdel test...

All the women's lives seem to revolve around one man: William (or his brother in the case of miss. Fox). Of course, it is written in the Victorian ages after all, which was not exactly a liberating time for women. It should also be noted that most of them want at least to improve their situation and in the end William is as much a tool for Sugar as visa versa.

The ending: as a book that does not really has a plot, it is not as strange that it does not really has ending. Though none of them quite sympathetic, the characters felt quite real to me, and in the end bringing some 'interesting' persons to life on paper is might be enough for a book to warrant its existence.

Title: Paper Towns
Author: John Green
My Review: It was just ok. After a couple of Green's books the vocabulous, whiny teenagers start to bore a bit.

Title: Probability and Computing: Randomized Algorithms and Probabilistic Analysis
Author: Michael Mitzenmacher

Title: And the Ass Saw the Angel
Author: Nick Cave
My Review: This is quite a hard book to review: I liked the atmosphere and most of the writing, but for a large part this is a difficult book to read.

Title: De zonderlinge avonturen van het geniale bommenmeisje
Author: Jonas Jonasson
My Review: actually liked it a bit better than the hundred year old man who climbed out of the window and disappeared.

Title: The Design of Everyday Things
Author: Donald A. Norman
My Review: Nice examples and an interesting treatment about why things often don't work as they should. Some of it is getting a bit outdated but some predictions are spot on (it is hard not to think of an iPhone when he describes his ideal calendar). Ironically, the book could be better structured, making it less suitable as a reference.

Title: Mr Mercedes (Bill Hodges Trilogy, #1)
Author: Stephen King
My Review: Enjoyable, but quite cliché...

Title: Lallend Vlees
Author: Frank D'hanis
My Review: Oorspronkelijk wat sceptisch, maar heb hem uiteindelijk graag gelezen. Erg grappig bij momenten.

Title: All Families Are Psychotic
Author: Douglas Coupland
My Review: Like most of Coupland books: clever, chaotic and quirky characters. I liked it.

Title: Waste: Uncovering the Global Food Scandal
Author: Tristram Stuart
My Review: Stuart provides a straightforward message to decrease environmental impact an solve world hunger: waste less food. Similarly to 'Eating Animals', the thesis is both well-founded by numbers and interviews as well are personal. Very recommended for the ecological minded!

Title: The Secret History
Author: Donna Tartt
My Review: Group of college students, dark secret, murder etc. Nothing out of the ordinary happens, but still a pleasant read.

Title: Vision: A Computational Investigation Into the Human Representation and Processing of Visual Information
Author: David  Marr
My Review: Difficult book to rate. I feel that it is a very personal and interesting viewpoint on the the perception of images, but I cannot shake the idea that it is also quite a bit outdated. It has a bit of an old AI feel where the focus was on algorithms rather than probability and networks. Contained some interesting concepts (for example, how we perceive depth and texture), but seemed to be both too technical and at the seem time too superficial to me...

Title: Atlas of Knowledge: Anyone Can Map
Author: Katy Börner

Title: De jongen die nooit heeft bestaan
Author: Sjón

Title: The Silkworm (Cormoran Strike, #2)
Author: Robert Galbraith
My Review: Really relaxing to read a well-written thriller once a while. Enjoyed it even more than 'the Cuckoo's Calling', 'Galbraith' really seems to shine when 'he' can write about the backstabbing world of tabloids and literary agencies.

Title: Inferring Phylogenies
Author: Joseph Felsenstein
Publisher: Sinauer Associates Is an Imprint of Oxford University Press
My Review: An impressive overview on the statistical methods used in phylogeny. Not for the faint of heart!

Title: The Fault in Our Stars
Author: John Green
My Review: I really enjoyed it, very likable characters and well written. Will definitely read more from John Green!

Title: Will Grayson, Will Grayson
Author: John Green
My Review: A very enjoyable novel about 'teens' problems'. Liked the gay theme throughout, without being depressing. Though the story is simple, one can see that all the characters have grown in their journey.

Title: Think Like a Freak
Author: Steven D. Levitt
My Review: Quite a quick and fun read with some nice stories and anecdotes. Like 'Thinking Fast an Slow' but a bit less academic.

Title: Brave New World
Author: Aldous Huxley
My Review: I was looking forward to this one, but I fear that the setting was more interesting than the story or characters.

Title: Biological Sequence Analysis
Author: Richard Durbin
Additional Authors: Sean R. Eddy, Anders Krogh, Graeme Mitchison
Bookshelves: ai, bio-engineering, bio-informatics, computer-science, references, math
Bookshelves with positions: ai (#12), bio-engineering (#15), bio-informatics (#9), computer-science (#21), references (#15), math (#27)
My Review:
Perhaps a quite old book, but very relevant for any bioinformatician! Have recently read Gusfields 'algorithms on strings', I think this one is the more relevant text on algorithms for biological sequences. The reason for this is that for working with real-life data a sound probabilistic framework is required! Anyone familiar with the standard machine learning tools will likely see how to link these methods and how to apply them for building classifiers for example.

The introduction on dynamics programming and HMM is good, though very descriptive. Might be necessary to consult additional material if you want to implement these tools yourself.

The part about inferring phylogenies was interesting and shows the difficulty of the field.

The last part about stochastic grammers and RNA was, to me extremely fascinating. The authors present some world which really goes at the heart of bioinformatics (or language modelling in general) and what we can and cannot do. A pity this section is only two chapters.

Title: Advanced Structured Prediction
Author: Sebastian Nowozin
Additional Authors: Peter V Gehler, Jeremy Jancsary, Christoph H. Lampert

Title: Algorithms on Strings, Trees and Sequences: Computer Science and Computational Biology
Author: Dan Gusfield
My Review: Good, but somewhat outdated overview of algorithms for processing strings for computational biology.

Title: Life's Ratchet: How Molecular Machines Extract Order from Chaos
Author: Peter M. Hoffmann

Title: Nanoscience: Invisible Powers Revealed
Author: Peter Forbes
My Review: Good light overview of the possibilities of nanotechnology. Not very technical, but nice pictures and examples.

Title: The Singularity is Near: When Humans Transcend Biology
Author: Ray Kurzweil
My Review:
Ray Kurzweil is prozac for scientists. While other scientific linked to the society, Ray paints a very bright future for us where GNR (genetics, nanotechnology and robotics) will solve solve all the world problems: medical, environmental, sociological...

If I read Kurzweil, I remember why it is fun to be an engineer, combining sciences from all different domains to create new technology to reshape mankind. I do not agree with all what he has to say (technology is not available to all and will likely create as many problems as it solves, do we really want to become demi-gods, immortal and living only for intellectual pleasures?), but it sure is an interesting read.

Title: Molecular Biology of the Cell
Author: Bruce Alberts
My Review: THE book about cells...

Title: The In Vitro Meat Cook Book
Author: Koert van Mensvoort
My Review:
This book is a nice 'what if' about how our culinary life could be changed by artificial meat. I used to think that In Vitro meat is a quite useless invention, vegan is more fruitful path, but this book has given me some 'food for thought'. This technology could allow to completely decouple meat from animal farming and thus we could completely reinvent some cultural phenomena associated with meat.

Though 45 hypothetical products (graded by degree of (un)realisticness) the reader is invited to think wether in in vitro meat could be part of our eating culture or would just be uncanny and disgusting.

Title: Glamorama
Author: Bret Easton Ellis
My Review:
Like other books of Ellis, this novel is often bothe boring and weird, intentionally. Victor Ward is a model who turns into a terrorist, for a not particularly clear reason. Just like American psycho, at some points the line between reality and the bizarre is blurred. For example, in the second half there is a camera crew following our protagonist during his involvement into some quite graphic novels.

All in all, the book alternates between dull and fascinating. Only for if you like the authors other work.

Title: Printing Things: Visions and Essentials for 3D Printing
Author: Claire Warnier
Additional Authors: Dries Verbruggen, Sven Ehmann, D Verbruggen/Unfold, Robert Klanten
My Review: Cool coffee table book that illustrates both the technological as well as the artistic possibilities of 3D printing. Looking forward to the time when our own printer arrives!

Title: Wat als?: serieuze wetenschappelijke antwoorden op absurde hypothetische vragen
Author: Randall Munroe
My Review:
To be fair: there are two reasons I bought this book: to support Randall Munroe, because I have been fan of his website for over half a decade and because I wanted to support a local bookstore which had a severe water leak...

I have read the duch version, which is quite weird.

Most of the essays can be read on Munroe's website. Online they can be enjoyed a bit more, because of the subtext and better formatted formulas. Only a third of the questions are new. Still, if you like weird and funny hypothetical science question, this is a book for you! Just do not expect a lot more compared to the blog.

Title: Show Your Work!: 10 Ways to Share Your Creativity and Get Discovered
Author: Austin Kleon
My Review: Nice, quick read for the hipster if you want to #ShareYourWork

Title: Legion and the Emperor's Soul
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Two excellent fantasy novels in the style of Brandon Sanderson: cool magic system, some likeable characters and a fast plot to keep you focused. Uncharacteristically for Sanderson this one is very concentrated, making it perfect as a quick read during a busy period.

Title: The Goldfinch
Author: Donna Tartt
My Review: Well written and quite enjoyable story with likable characters, but to be honest it could benefit from being a couple of hundreds of pages shorter...

Title: Introduction to Computational Genomics
Author: Nello Cristianini
My Review: Very fun book that explains bioinformatics at the hand of 10 small case studies: study of mutations in the HIV virus, origin of SARS, internal clock of plants. Quick read but an accessible introduction to the field.

Title: American Gods (American Gods, #1)
Author: Neil Gaiman
My Review:
Do the old gods still have a place in the new world? Gaiman explores in this book how the gods of Europe, Asia and Africa struggle with being replaced by newcomers such as Media or Internet.

As the title suggests, a very American book and easy to see why it has become a modern classic.

Title: The Joker: Death of the Family
Author: Scott Snyder
Additional Authors: Gail Simone, Scott Lobdell, John Layman, Peter J. Tomasi, Ann Nocenti, Kyle Higgins, Adam Glass, Fabian Nicieza, James Tynion IV, Ed Benes, Patrick Gleason, Jason Fabok, Fernando Dagnino, Eddy Barrows, Brett Booth, Rafa Sandoval, Jordi Tarrogona, Greg Capullo

Title: The Cuckoo's Calling (Cormoran Strike, #1)
Author: Robert Galbraith
My Review: A good detective novel. Probably not the Magnus opus of Rowling, but likely for her just as fun to write as to read.

Title: Classical Mechanics: The Theoretical Minimum (Theoretical Minimum #1)
Author: Leonard Susskind
My Review: Very quick and lucid overview of classical mechanics! Delivers what it promises: a fun overview of the field in which most of the math is introduced and used. Recommended for those who enjoyed physics but ended up studying something else, as the cover tells.

Title: Doctor Sleep (The Shining, #2)
Author: Stephen King
My Review: Quite a relaxing (though not super memorable) read.

Title: Kernel Methods for Pattern Analysis
Author: John Shawe-Taylor
My Review: Very clearly written background manual about the different kernel-based algorithms and the different kernels for specific tasks. The derivations of generalisation bound where the most lucid I have ever encountered.

Title: Nostalgie van het geluk
Author: Amélie Nothomb
My Review: Typical for the latter autobiographical work of Nothomb, this is mainly a book with her being awkward and cute with not much of a point or story.

Title: The Tiny Book of Tiny Stories, Vol. 2
Author: Joseph Gordon-Levitt
My Review: Not as good as the first one, still a delightful read.

Title: Cooking for Geeks: Real Science, Great Hacks, and Good Food
Author: Jeff Potter
My Review: One of the coolest cooking book/popular science I have ever read! Potter links cooking with the mindset of a nerd/geek/(computer) scientist in a way to encourage exploring and tinkering in the kitchen. There are very useful graphs and science facts (such as tables with suggestions of which flavours to combine, temperature charts when collagen or gelatine starts to denaturate...), interesting interviews with chefs, food engineers, reporters and other people. There are experiments with liquid nitrogen and sugar cookies, tips for sorting your shelves... One nearly forgets it also contain quite a lot of neat recipes. In short both a useful and entertaining book for every geek who likes to cook!

Title: The Illustrated Man
Author: Ray Bradbury
My Review: Series of science fiction short stories. Most of them are quite entertaining.

Title: Kind van een vreemde
Author: Alan Hollinghurst
My Review: I somewhat liked other books of Hollinghurst, but I did not enjoy this one. To slow, to British, to upper class...

Title: Cities Are Good for You: The Genius of the Metropolis
Author: Leo Hollis
My Review: Hollis describes the advantages and challenges which accompany living in a city. Contained some interesting anecdotes, but overal not a very gripping read, with a not very strong message.

Title: Can't We Talk about Something More Pleasant?
Author: Roz Chast

Title: Een mooie jonge vrouw
Author: Tommy Wieringa
Publisher: Stichting Collectieve Propaganda van het Nederlandse Boek
My Review: A fine short story about love and vegetarism. Quite ok for a free book.

Title: How to Talk with Practically Anybody about Practically Anything
Author: Barbara Walters

Title: Stuff Matters: Exploring the Marvelous Materials That Shape Our Man-Made World
Author: Mark Miodownik
My Review: As with any good popular science writer: Miodownk makes the ordinary, plastic, glass, chocolate... seem extraordinary. Good read.

Title: The Book of Trees: Visualizing Branches of Knowledge
Author: Manuel Lima
My Review: Very nice collection of data visualisations using trees, both historical as modern. Lima shows the power and beauty of using tree as a way to represent the hierarchical information in data and knowledge.

Title: The Way of Kings (The Stormlight Archive, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: The characters took a while to grow at me, but as always Sanderson succeeds in drawing likeable characters in an interesting word with a cool magic system. I am looking forward to the other ones in this series!

Title: Intuition Pumps And Other Tools for Thinking
Author: Daniel C. Dennett
My Review: Dennett provides an entertaining and though-provoking set of thought experiments about topics as diverse as free will, evolution and computer science. Some of them are probably somewhat weird and artificial to the non-philosopher, but most a genuine interesting. Pleasant read due to the short chapters.

Title: A Wild Ride Through the Night
Author: Walter Moers
My Review: Moers uses a series of drawings of Gustave Doré to tell the tale a boy send on a quest by Death himself.

Title: Waarover ik praat als ik over hardlopen praat
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review: Though I really love Murakami, reading a book in which he muses about his hobby is kind of a boring read...

Title: Caffeinated: How Our Daily Habit Helps, Hurts, and Hooks Us
Author: Murray Carpenter
My Review: Yesterday I was on a machine learning conference. This book made me realise that all the researcher were taking a drug to help them perform. Carpenter sketches the story of a white powder we take multiple times a day in our soda and beverages. Though I found it does not make the top ten of the best non-fiction books I have read, it certainly leaves an impression.

Title: Cooked: A Natural History of Transformation
Author: Michael Pollan
My Review:
Fire! Water! Air! Earth! Pollan shows how to unlock the avatar state with cooking.

In this delightful book it is explored how cooking has brought humans from nature to culture. Pollan arguments that taking your time to make a stew or bake a bread learns us to appreciate how we use nearly alchemical processes to transform ingredients to food.

In the chapter 'Fire' he takes us to the fire pits where pigs are roasted whole. At first this seemed a dreadfully dull chapter to me, but the delicious anecdotes and musings on the spiritual and divine meaning of baking meat made it a surprising interesting read.

In 'Water', it is discussed how humanity has transcended from public roasting to private cooking in pots. Could also be called the now of dicing onions.

'Air' is about the quest of bringing air to porridge to create bread, the food of civilisation.

Finally, 'Earth' is about the cold fire: fermentation. It discusses how the élan vital of microarginsims can change milk to cheese and even give fruit juice the power to alter minds.

It should be clear that I really enjoyed this one, in my opinion good non-fiction can easily compete with any fantasy or thriller.

Title: The Maker Movement Manifesto: Rules for Innovation in the New World of Crafters, Hackers, and Tinkerers
Author: Mark Hatch

Title: Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (Harry Potter, #6)
Author: J.K. Rowling

Title: All of Statistics: A Concise Course in Statistical Inference
Author: Larry Wasserman
My Review: Very good reference on notions on probability, statistics and machine learning. Not ideal to learn the matter from scratch, but ideal to refresh and supplement your knowledge when you do a PhD.

Title: Eleanor Rigby
Author: Douglas Coupland
My Review:
The protagonist is lonely middle-aged women who is lonely.

Not terribly memorable, but a pleasant read nonetheless.

Title: The Great Gatsby
Author: F. Scott Fitzgerald
My Review: I must confess that I have read this only after watching the movie, which is why I am probably somewhat biased. As a book about the obsession of love and the emptiness of the american dream, this book seems to be as relevant nowadays as 90 years ago.

Title: Oliver Byrne: The First Six Books of the Elements of Euclid
Author: Werner Oechslin

Title: All My Friends are Superheroes
Author: Andrew Kaufman
My Review:
Tom is a normal guy, whose friends all have incredible superpowers such as an above-human to procrastination abilities, the power to travel trough time (though having the power to not do this would be the trick) and the gift to absorb stress from others.

Being turned invisible to his girlfriend, Tom has to save his relation without any superpowers at all...

Title: On Bullshit
Author: Harry G. Frankfurt
My Review: A great piece of bullshit on bullshit (but wit some surprisingly smart insights on what we consider to be truth).

Title: Moonwalking with Einstein: The Art and Science of Remembering Everything
Author: Joshua Foer
My Review:
Joshua Foer describes how he became interested in a memory competition and, on a dare, won it.

Interesting book on the philosophy of memory; are we born with a knack for remembering things or can we train it? Foer suggests it is basically an exercise in self-discipline and creativity. He is fair in the sense that the gift of being able to memorise shopping lists might be of marginal relevance in a world containing post-its and smart phones. The persons with the perfect memory (both through training or because they are prodigies ) might not be better of than the forgetful people like you and me.

A good read about the philosophy of the memory.

Title: The Tiny Book of Tiny Stories, Vol. 1
Author: Joseph Gordon-Levitt
My Review: Only 80 pages long, with about one sentence per story, this little book is a delightful snack to recharge your batteries.

Title: De kleurloze Tsukuru Tazaki en zijn pelgrimsjaren
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review:
Hoewel Murakami weer zijn vaste thema's behoud (los van de wereld staan, een verloren jeugd, laveren tussen droom en werkelijkheid), blijft hij ook in zijn laatste werk boeien.
Het verhaal gaat over een 'kleurloze' everyman die zestien jaar na datum een jeugdtrauma plaats probeert te geven. Murakami weet zoals altijd zijn lezer te vereenzelvigen met de gevoelens en ervaringen van zijn hoofdpersonage.

Title: The Hundred-Year-Old Man Who Climbed Out of the Window and Disappeared
Author: Jonas Jonasson
My Review: Not terrible original (a man who has no interest in politics ends up being the driving force of the most important events of the last century) but quite funny and entertaining.

Title: The Casual Vacancy
Author: J.K. Rowling
My Review:
This one took my quite long to finish and I am a bit torn how to rate it. For me it took a while before I felt that I knew the characters well enough to follow the plot well. Only in the last 100 pages I have come to realise how human and real they feel to me. In contrast the plot (though there was really a very strong plot, it was more following the live of the cast for a couple of months) was not that very gripping to me personally, perhaps because I am not British or particularly political minded.

I would conclude that I am quite impressed with how it is written, but the themes are, for me personally, less my cup of tea.

Any comparisons to a certain heptalogy I will let to those only reading two or three children's books a year.

Title: Shampoo Planet
Author: Douglas Coupland
My Review: Another novel about teens that clash with consumer culture. It was ok.

Title: Amarillo (Blacksad, #5)
Author: Juan Díaz Canales
My Review: After 5 episodes the comic has lost some steam and novelty. By now it seems to be little more than BD noir with animals...

Title: Learning Kernel Classifiers: Theory and Algorithms
Author: Ralf Herbrich
My Review: Good introduction to kernel methods and learning theory.

Title: The Encyclopedia of Early Earth
Author: Isabel Greenberg
My Review:
The perfect Christmas reading!

It tells the story of a storyteller in search of a missing part of his soul, being thwarted and aided by the gods. Very warm (and often funny stories) with gorgeous illustration.

Title: The Signal and the Noise: The Art and Science of Prediction
Author: Nate Silver
My Review: Contained some very interesting things although some of the cases are less my cup of tea (the multiple chapters on baseball and the stock marked). Though Silver gives us some nice insights about prediction, it is somewhat disorganised. Overall a nice layman book about the ideas of statistics and machine learning in everyday life.

Title: How to Build a Brain: A Neural Architecture for Biological Cognition
Author: Chris Eliasmith
Bookshelves: bio-engineering, consciousness, computer-science, to-read, ai, references
Bookshelves with positions: bio-engineering (#6), consciousness (#12), computer-science (#11), to-read (#9), ai (#10), references (#7)

Title: Into the Cool: Energy Flow, Thermodynamics, and Life
Author: Eric D. Schneider
My Review: Very interesting book that links non equilibrium thermodynamics (NET) with all kinds of self-organizing systems. In contrasts to many other books (such as Design in Nature, which tried to bring the same message but fell flat) this one gives many experimental overview and cites a wealth of sources to make its point. Thermodynamics has always been my favorite branch of physics and this book nicely shows the beauty, generality and elegance of this theory.

Title: The Alloy of Law (Mistborn, #4)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Nice short follow up of the general mist born trilogy. It is alway fun to read about the metal-based magic system, especially with the Legend of Korra back on tv :)

Title: The Hero of Ages (Mistborn, #3)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: A satisfying ending to a very good trilogy!

Title: How to Create a Mind: The Secret of Human Thought Revealed
Author: Ray Kurzweil
My Review:
Meh, I had high hopes for it, thinking it would give technical insights into (true) AI. Having read multiple books on AI and brain science, I guess this book is (like many other popular science books) a linear combination of other works. Give an overview of the working of the brain, give an intro to machine learning/neural networks/evolutionary algorithms, add some Turing machines, Gödel incompleteness etc and top off with some philosophical discussions about zombies and free will and voilla, you have your standard AI popular science novel.

In the end, it was well written and contained some interesting ideas (with some good notes on the chapters at the end of the book). It did not have many new things compared to other (Hawkins, Hofstadter, Penrose, Seung...) writers' books.

Title: Coraline
Author: Neil Gaiman
My Review: Nice children's story. Overall I liked the stop motion adaptation a little better, but the book is also good.

Title: The Well of Ascension (Mistborn, #2)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
Liked it. Typically with trilogies the middle book is the weakest (of course, I have the read the final one to see if this true). This one builds farther on the issues that were left hanging on the last one. I liked the character development, though the story hasn't progressed a lot in this book.

Very curious to read the final one!

Title: The Final Empire (Mistborn, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review: Really enjoyed this one! Cool magic system (like a video game!), interesting characters and a fast and gripping plot!

Title: Getting Things Done: Prettig en efficiënt werken zonder stress
Author: David    Allen
My Review: Like all self-help books part useful tips, part page filling. I will try to implement the basic idea in my life :)

Title: The Viral Storm: The Dawn of a New Pandemic Age
Author: Nathan Wolfe
My Review: Many non-fiction books claim to be suspenseful - this one is right.

Title: The Good Man Jesus and the Scoundrel Christ
Author: Philip Pullman
My Review: Retelling of the legend of Jesus Christ from an atheist's point of view.

Title: An Abundance of Katherines
Author: John Green
My Review:
Colin is a child progeny, but aspires to be remembered as a genius (something he's not). To create order of the hurricane of Katherines that have dumped him and to attain his place in psychology text books, he tries to develop a formula to predict relationship failure.

It was nice to read for a change about a 'special' kid who is not a mini Sheldon (strongly autistic of Asperger), but is in a way just a normal teenager (though an awkward one).

Title: Gaussian Processes for Machine Learning
Author: Carl Edward Rasmussen
My Review: Good book on GP, with a strong theoretical foundation. Good reference for people who work with kernel and are interested in the Bayesian approach.

Title: Connectome: How the Brain's Wiring Makes Us Who We Are
Author: Sebastian Seung
My Review:
This book was quite a pleasant read, especially compared to some of the other books on brain science I read. Seung gives a very clear and well structured overview of his ideas: from the concepts and principles of the connectome paradigm (basically the idea that a complete map of neuron wiring would allow us to completely understand the brain) to the techniques for constructing such a brain model to some philosophical consequences.

The reason that I give a relatively low rating is that I found the book quite full of 'hot air' (I also thought this of Seung's TED talk). Being a bioinformatician myself, I recognize the same type of hype that was around the human genome project. We can sequence a person for less than a year's wage, yet not all genetic diseases have been vanished from the face of the earth. Similarly, Seung does not really delve in detail how we will use the connectome to read memories or cure depressions. Though, this might be just me nitpicking.

It is also hard to take someone serious who 'mocks' genetics, but at the same time claims neural wiring is the holy grail to solve all of our eartly problems (literally).

On the whole this is an enjoyable book, but from a scientific point of view, it is a bit too 'shallow'. A better approach to brain science would be 'On Intelligence', at least IMHO.

Title: Memoirs of a Geisha
Author: Arthur Golden
My Review: The story of a nine year old girl who is sold to become a geisha. Very beautifully and personally written as it is based on real events based on personal conversations between the author and protagonist.

Title: The Where, the Why, and the How: 75 Artists Illustrate Wondrous Mysteries of Science
Author: Matt LaMothe
Additional Authors: Julia Rothman, Jenny Volvovski, David Macaulay
My Review: Great book for popular science lovers. Interesting sessions and very nice illustrations!

Title: Abstract City
Author: Christoph Niemann
My Review: Great read, very creative!

Title: Turing's Cathedral: The Origins of the Digital Universe
Author: George Dyson
My Review:
I find it difficult to rate this book. The history of the development of the computer is an interesting one, with the main characters some of the greatest minds of the first half of the 20th century. You can feel the excitement and wonder in the development of the this technology which the goal of modeling (and controlling) the weather, simulating evolution and, of course, making the atom bomb.

The main issue with this book, in my opinion, is that some chapter somewhat lacked focus with respect to the main message.

Title: After dark
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review: Do you know the feeling when you are awake in the middle of the night, because you can't sleep or you have to travel to some place? Your bones ache and you are both more drowsy and alert than during the day and all is silent. This book perfectly reconstructs such an atmosphere in which you believe you share the world with only a select number of people.

Title: All the Buildings in New York (That I've Drawn So Far)
Author: James Gulliver Hancock

Title: Skippy Dies
Author: Paul Murray
My Review: An Irish boarding school pupil dies in a doughnut-eating context. This novel has a somewhat chaotic plot, but has many very interesting characters. I enjoyed it.

Title: Cat Getting Out of a Bag and Other Observations
Author: Jeffrey Brown

Title: Logicomix: Een epische zoektocht naar de waarheid
Author: Apostolos K. Doxiadis

Title: Learning with Kernels: Support Vector Machines, Regularization, Optimization, and Beyond
Author: Bernhard Schölkopf
My Review: Both practical and interesting. I thought I knew something about kernels, but apparently there was/still quite some more to them :)

Title: Prince of the Elves (Amulet, #5)
Author: Kazu Kibuishi
My Review: Not a lot happens in this part. We learn some backstory about the characters and the stone, but none is too shocking. I would have had somewhat more story rather than somewhat meaningless fight scenes. Still, the art remains rather gorgeous.

Title: The Manga Guide to Statistics
Author: Shin Takahashi
My Review: Very funny introduction to statistics. Doesn't go beyond high-school stuff, gives a quite complete and practical overview of the basics.

Title: Wonderful Life With the Elements: The Periodic Table Personified
Author: Bunpei Yorifuji
My Review:
I have complained that I is very hard to find good popular science books on chemistry. After reading this I am afraid that the bar for this niche has been set far to high for these books.

This is a wonderful read, very nice illustrations, funny and contains lots of interesting little facts about the different elements!

Title: The Red House
Author: Mark Haddon
My Review: Not an easy read due to the constant switching of perspective and the absence of quotation marks. It did help to set the atmosphere of the intertwined lives of the characters. Overall I think it is a good read and doesn't deserve all the negative comments (it is the the curious incident of the dog at night time, can we please move on?)

Title: Marx's Das Kapital: A Biography
Author: Francis Wheen
My Review: I am not really a history freak, but it was an interesting and short book about history around 'Das Kapital'.

Title: The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory
Author: Vladimir N. Vapnik
My Review: Well, it's a book about the mathematical foundation of statistical learning, so it is not an easy read. Gives an interesting overview in the theory behind support vector machines and how they can be applied for classification, regression and density estimation. I liked the philosophical intermezzos.

Title: The Wise Man's Fear (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #2)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review: Nice read, but at some points a bit too long with an unfocused plot. The different events are a bit too long to keep the readers attention.

Title: Predicting Structured Data
Author: Golchan Bakir
My Review: Good book on structured output prediction. The introductory chapters and some of the latter ones gave some interesting and novel insights on kernel methods in general to me. I particularly liked the tutorial about energy models. Other chapters were somewhat too mathy and technical to bring their message across.

Title: Fullmetal Alchemist, Vol. 27 (Fullmetal Alchemist, #27)
Author: Hiromu Arakawa
My Review: A very satisfying ending to an excellent series!

Title: Metamagical Themas: Questing for the Essence of Mind and Pattern
Author: Douglas R. Hofstadter

Title: The Superorganism: The Beauty, Elegance, and Strangeness of Insect Societies
Author: Bert Hölldobler

Title: Bayesian Reasoning and Machine Learning
Author: David Barber
My Review: Very good general machine learning/graphical model book, much more accessible than Bishop! I liked the emphasis on missing values of some of the chapters. Would recommend the middle part of the book as a good, but slightly unorthodox introduction to machine learning.

Title: The Stonekeeper's Curse (Amulet, #2)
Author: Kazu Kibuishi
My Review: I have to agree that this series seems to manifests lots of well known tropes and clichés, but the high emotional stakes and the gorgeous drawing make sure I am very much looking forward to the remainder of this series

Title: Aikido Weapons Techniques: The Wooden Sword, Stick and Knife of Aikido
Author: Phong Thong Dang
My Review: Nice short overview of the use of weapons (boken, jo and tanto) in aikido. Contains reasonable clear pictures and some (solo) exercises.

Title: Fullmetal Alchemist, Vol. 3 (Fullmetal Alchemist, #3)
Author: Hiromu Arakawa
My Review: I actually read this one before number 2. Oops...

Title: Fullmetal Alchemist, Vol. 2 (Fullmetal Alchemist, #2)
Author: Hiromu Arakawa
My Review: The plot thickens!

Title: Fullmetal Alchemist, Vol. 1 (Fullmetal Alchemist, #1)
Author: Hiromu Arakawa
My Review: Typically for long series like these, it will probably take some volumes to grow to me. As I really like these types of blends between science and magic I am looking forward to it!

Title: Angry White Pyjamas: A Scrawny Oxford Poet Takes Lessons from the Tokyo Riot Police
Author: Robert Twigger
My Review: As an beginning aikidoka myself I enjoyed this book. Reminiscent to some of the works of Nothomb, this book explores the cultural differences between Japan and the West.

Title: Thinking, Fast and Slow
Author: Daniel Kahneman
My Review:
An superb book about human behavior!

In this work the duality between the rational decision making and using your 'gut feeling'. Through the description of many experiments and thought-provoking little questions to the reader the author shows that most people are not as rational as they might think.

Really liked the small review concepts at the end of each chapter!

Title: Das Labyrinth der Träumenden Bücher (Zamonien, #6)
Author: Walter Moers
My Review: The first Walter Moers work that disappointed me. What I've previously liked about the Zamonia novels is that each book is self contained, the characters are likable, the story is gripping and is finally completed. This labyrinth of the dreaming books is the sequel to the acclaimed city of the dreaming books, which completely and satisfactory ended. This is a thin repetition of the previous success, with hardly any new personages, creatures or concepts this serie is famed for. As this book is apparently a (lengthy) prologue, Moers still has a chance to somewhat redeem this, frankly unnecessary novel.

Title: Hey Nostradamus!
Author: Douglas Coupland
My Review:
This is the story of four people who's lives are affected by a high-school massacre, spaced over several decades. It deals with love, grief, despair and hope.

A very beautiful, well written novel with personages you can't help to empathize with. Even the religious nut.

Title: The Name of the Wind (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #1)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss

Title: Steal Like an Artist: 10 Things Nobody Told You About Being Creative
Author: Austin Kleon

Title: Code
Author: Charles Petzold
My Review: One of these popular science books you wish you have read them when you were younger. Petzold builds a computer using relays and imagination. Though somewhat dated, this is a gentle overview of computer architecture.

Title: A Practical Guide to Linux Commands, Editors, and Shell Programming
Author: Mark G. Sobell

Title: On Intelligence: How a New Understanding of the Brain Will Lead to the Creation of Truly Intelligent Machines
Author: Jeff Hawkins
My Review: A very good and interesting book about the nature of (artificial) intelligence and the workings of brains. The author brings a clear theory, nicely framed from where it came from and what the implications are.

Title: Mathematics of Life: Unlocking the Secrets of Existence
Author: Ian Stewart
My Review: Quite interesting, but I"ve read most of the things elsewhere.

Title: Blankets
Author: Craig Thompson
My Review: A perfect story over love, life and religion.

Title: The Hobbit
Author: J.R.R. Tolkien
My Review: Re-read this after 10 years before the upcoming movie. An excellent non-doorstopper fantasy story!

Title: パン屋再襲撃
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review:
Two friends with an immense hunger attempt to rob a bakery.
Like Sleep this is an utmost charming little story that blurs the line between dream and reality. Again beautiful illustrated by Kat Menschik.

Title: The Quantum Universe: Everything That Can Happen Does Happen
Author: Brian Cox
My Review: Given the piles of quantum physics books 'for the layman', this one still manage to stand out. By making use of clever analogies they manage to explain the difficult concepts in a clear way. Just as QED popular science on its best!

Title: Castle Waiting: The Curse of  Brambly Hedge (Castle Waiting)
Author: Linda Medley

Title: A Dance with Dragons (A Song of Ice and Fire, #5)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: Sustainable Energy - Without the Hot Air
Author: David J.C. MacKay
My Review:
A book of which you have high expectations and that doesn't disappoint.

I wish more people could give the numbers and formulas for the layman.

Title: Drie Schimmen
Author: Cyril Pedrosa
My Review: Very beautifully drawn and a very nice, sad story

Title: Supercooperators: The Mathematics of Evolution, Altruism and Human Behaviour {Or, Why We Need Each Other to Succeed}
Author: M.A. Nowak
My Review:
I guess that after 'Evolutionary Dynamics' this one could only disappoint. This is a bad example of presenting your complicated field off research to the broad public.

Removing all the equations out of ED was probably fair as most people have no message to this. Though it was not an added value to add a truckload of anecdotes and little histories of all the people involved. Yes, professor Nowak has met everybody in science who is worth knowing, from Dawkins to Hawkins and has written more Science and Nature papers than anyone cares to count. But I would think thing this biological equivalent of the theory of everything is interesting in its own? And why are there no pictures? ED was a very visual book and I frankly don't know if people who haven't read this one will be able to follow everything that was presented...

Overall, I do not think this was a very bad book, it only could be SO much more.

Title: A Feast for Crows (A Song of Ice and Fire, #4)
Author: George R.R. Martin
My Review: Despite a lot of people were apparently disappointed, I really liked this one. Keep em coming!

Title: Decoding the Universe: How the New Science of Information Is Explaining Everything in the Cosmos, from Our Brains to Black Holes
Author: Charles Seife
My Review:
A very nice book! Makes a very light and pleasant reading, even for a popular science book. Most of the concepts are already known to the casual reader of physics book, but the link with information theory was an interesting new way to look at them. At moments very funny.

The chapter about biology was very poorly written though and interrupted the flow of the book.

Title: Waar de tijgers thuis zijn
Author: Jean-Marie Blas de Roblès
Additional Authors: Karin Santen, Martine Vosmaer, Martine Woudt
My Review: Een vlot boek om te lezen maar helaas niet zo fantastisch als de achterflap doet vermoeden. Vrij chaotisch verhaal, maar kan wel nog relatief boeien.

Title: The Psychedelic Experience: A Manual Based on the Tibetan Book of the Dead
Author: Timothy Leary
Additional Authors: Ralph Metzner, Richard Alpert, Daniel Pinchbeck
My Review: Interesting book.

Title: Networks of the Brain
Author: Olaf Sporns
My Review:
This is quite a difficult book to rate. Though it was was well written by an expert in the field, the overload of information can make it a less enjoyable popular science book.

I know quite a lot about evolution, complexity, dynamical systems and the like, but nearly nothing about brains. At moment it seems Sporns had a reader with opposite background in mind as he freely throws in terms of neuroanatomy, mostly explaining only the concepts of other fields. But apart from this, this it contains a wealth of interesting information, linking ideas discussed by well known scientists such as Dawkins, Wagner, Strogatz, Friston etc.

Definitely recommend it to those interested in brain science and, to some extend, to those with interest in complexity, AI and the likes

Title: Optimal Control and Estimation
Author: Robert F. Stengel
My Review: Good manual for control theory. Would recommend it as a (budget friendly) reference.

Title: A Storm of Swords (A Song of Ice and Fire, #3)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: Tuer le Père
Author: Amélie Nothomb
My Review: Boring and unoriginal combination of her previous books.

Title: De jacht op het verloren schaap
Author: Haruki Murakami
My Review: For some reason I did not particulary like this one of Murakami...

Title: The Road to Reality: A Complete Guide to the Laws of the Universe
Author: Roger Penrose

Title: A Clash of Kings  (A Song of Ice and Fire, #2)
Author: George R.R. Martin

Title: Dieren eten
Author: Jonathan Safran Foer
My Review: A very moving book.

Title: In Pursuit of the Unknown: 17 Equations That Changed the World
Author: Ian Stewart
My Review: A very clear and interesting text. Stewart knows to tell some interesting new things about even the most well known equations. A good read for everyone (no higher math than high school is required).

Title: A Game of Thrones (A Song of Ice and Fire, #1)
Author: George R.R. Martin
My Review: At least as good as the television series. Not a lot more to say.

Title: Design in Nature: How the Constructal Law Governs Evolution in Biology, Physics, Technology, and Social Organization
Author: Adrian Bejan
My Review:
Like some people before me, I was was somewhat disappointed in this book.

First of all, Bejan is very arrogant. He is not the first, nor will be the last popular science author to be this, but it quite insufferable of him to keep repeating that he has surpassed Darwin and can make every (important) thing in nature clear by performing his subfield of thermodynamics. Of course prof. Bejan keeps reminding us that it is only natural that the ignorant masses can't recognize his genius. (And he doesn't like Communism).

The so-called constructal law is extremely vage. Design in nature arises to maximizes a 'flow'. What kind of flow? Would it prefer a flow of 100 l of water per second or of 100 l of air? Is there some theoretical derivation of this law, based on the laws of thermodynamics? Why don't I know this if I have read the book?

No formal discription of the law is given. Every chapter contains a couple of (rather badly structured) examples. Though some of them are quite interesting, I fail to see any need for any constructal low. Trees are tree-shaped because they need to keep a flow of water (to transport nutrients, keep their cells turgid and keep their floem moving). This could be predicted by the principles of evolution, same for the animals' movement.

In short, this book could be really interesting but should have been better (and more critically!) edited.

Title: The 13½ Lives of Captain Bluebear (Zamonia, #1)
Author: Walter Moers
My Review:
Though perhaps not the best of the Zamonian novels (that would probably be Rumo) I nevertheless enjoyed every one of its 700 pages. The strength of this book is not the story or even the main character (who is pretty generic) but the enormous wealth and descriptions of the different fantastical places, creatures and habits. In my opinion the imagination of Moers is superior than, for example, Rowling's as he goes farther than merely building on folclore but creating a world completely of his own which, although perhaps somewhat silly, is also taken seriously and consequent through the different novels.
If you liked the classical fantasy books as a child such as Rowling, Dahl or Carrol than this is probably a nice guilty pleasure.

Title: The Alchemaster's Apprentice: A Culinary Tale from Zamonia by Optimus Yarnspinner (Zamonia, #5)
Author: Walter Moers

Title: The Extended Phenotype: The Long Reach of the Gene
Author: Richard Dawkins

Title: An Introduction to Information Theory: Symbols, Signals and Noise
Author: John Robinson Pierce
My Review: Interesting with a lot of applications. With moments somewhat old fashioned.

Title: Voor ik ga slapen
Author: S.J. Watson
My Review: Very thrilling, an excellent book you can't put down!

Title: Bio-Inspired Artificial Intelligence: Theories, Methods, and Technologies
Author: Dario Floreano
My Review:
A very interesting book! Discusses some of the most important fields in and methods in AI with the complexity in biology as a red line (from methods inspired by evolution, to cells, to development ending with behaviour of groups of organisms).
Has a lot of examples, most of them dealing with robotics (I myself am a bioscience engineer/bioinformatician and would have liked to see some other applications).
Not very heavy on its math, basic high-school calculus would suffice to understand most concepts in some detail.

Title: QED: The Strange Theory of Light and Matter
Author: Richard Feynman

Title: Brain, Mind, and the Structure of Reality
Author: Paul L. Nunez
My Review: Interesting book that tries to link relativity, quantum physics and thermodynamics to the mind-body problem. Somewhat limited in his explanation of certain topics but Nunez is able to make his point somewhat better then Penrose in the emperor's new mind.

Title: Aikido and the Dynamic Sphere: An Illustrated Introduction
Author: Adele Westbrook

Title: Inbound Marketing: Get Found Using Google, Social Media, and Blogs
Author: Brian Halligan
My Review: Surprisingly interesting.

Title: My Green City: Back to Nature with Attitude and Style
Author: Robert Klanten
My Review: Cool book! Title says it all!

Title: Six Not-So-Easy Pieces: Einstein's Relativity, Symmetry, and Space-Time
Author: Richard Feynman
My Review: Excellent little book that explains the gist of relativity. Concepts are explained using math a smart high schooler should be able to follow. Lot's better than the one-chapters introductions of relativity you find in Hawkins or Greene

Title: Over sneeuwkristallen en zebrastrepen: De wereld volgens de wiskunde
Author: Ian Stewart

Title: Illegal Drugs: A Complete Guide to their History, Chemistry, Use, and Abuse
Author: Paul Gahlinger
My Review: Excellent objective reference for all kinds of drugs.

Title: Gödel's Proof
Author: Ernest Nagel
Additional Authors: James Roy Newman, Douglas R. Hofstadter
My Review: Cute little book that gives an interesting overview on mathematical systems and their limitations.

Title: The Emperor's New Mind: Concerning Computers, Minds and the Laws of Physics
Author: Roger Penrose
My Review:
A book about turing machines, Gödel's theorem, cosmology, quantum mechanics, neurology and consciousness? I was sold!

Penrose is, IMHO, the best writer about physics. His style is friendly and relaxed but thorough. I do not follow his thesis that it is not possible to construct hard AI and brains need an quantum physical element to be understood. But this book deals with such interesting subjects and themes about the universe and our place in it, it is impossible not to be fascinated.

Title: Evolution in Four Dimensions: Genetic, Epigenetic, Behavioral, and Symbolic Variation in the History of Life
Author: Eva Jablonka
My Review: A very good and enjoyable book about evolution. This book is in a similar vein as 'Evolutionary development biology', where the gene centered view we all know and love thanks to Dawkings is critically evaluated. The authors skillfully lay their theories using interesting examples, critical dialogues and very funny and nicely drawn cartoons.

Title: Life, the Universe and Everything (Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, #3)
Author: Douglas Adams

Title: The Restaurant at the End of the Universe (Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, #2)
Author: Douglas Adams

Title: Information Theory, Inference and Learning Algorithms
Author: David J.C. MacKay
My Review:
Excellent book about diverse topics in machine learning, statistics, information theory etc. Many exercises and applications.
Free to download on the internet!

Title: I Am a Strange Loop
Author: Douglas R. Hofstadter
My Review:
Hofstadter gives us a scientific model for the soul. Beautifully written, very personal (though sometimes a bit too personal!)
A must for everyone who enjoyed GEB!

Title: Control Theory and Systems Biology
Author: Pablo A. Iglesias
My Review: A bit to

Title: Rumo & His Miraculous Adventures (Zamonia, #3)
Author: Walter Moers
My Review:
This might be one of the best stories I've ever read! This book is full of ideas, interesting characters, places and creatures so well developed they feel almost real. Don't be fooled in thinking this is (only) a children's book: it deals with themes as love and courage but also with darker stuff like death and sadism.
Moers can easily compete with Rowling, Dahl and Ende. His drawings are really fun to watch and make it even more memorable.
Something that struck me is that in the 745 pages of this book only 4 female characters are named: only one is relevant for the plot... In 'the city of the dreaming books' there were no female characters. This is quite odd as Rala is just as realistic as any other person.

Title: Bizarre wetenschap: Vreemde en opzienbarende experimenten
Author: Reto U. Schneider

Title: The Wild Things
Author: Dave Eggers
My Review: Was a bit disappointing (I did not see the film version)

Title: Ecological Developmental Biology: Integrating Epigenetics, Medicine, and Evolution: An Integrated Approach to Embryology, Evolution, and Medicine
Author: Scott F. Gilbert
My Review:
An extremely interesting book that combines the branches of ecology, development biology, epigenetics, medicine, toxicology and most important, evolution etc. Lot's of cool examples are given.

Like the best of (popular) science it makes you question everything you thought you knew about the subject (evolution).

Warning: may make you paranoid about endocrine disruptors.

Title: Some Rain Must Fall: And Other Stories
Author: Michel Faber

Title: The Rain Before it Falls
Author: Jonathan Coe
My Review: Very touching

Title: Under the Skin
Author: Michel Faber
My Review: Not as thrilling and unexpected as the cover would let you believe but still and enjoyable book. I won't tell the theme, but it is idd somewhat different then expected.

Title: Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning
Author: Christopher M. Bishop
My Review:
Very good reference for machine learning and data mining.
I found it somewhat technical and abstract in times (there are no real life examples), some concepts can be explained a bit more intuitively.

Author: Brian Greene

Author: Paulo Coelho

Title: Sync: The Emerging Science of Spontaneous Order
Author: Steven H. Strogatz
My Review:
This is a marvelous book! Strogatz has the gift to explain complex mathematical theories with simple and clear analogies. He gives us examples from biology, sociology, modern physics, cosmology, traffic science etc to prove chaos theory is not some abstract idea only useful to keep some pale eccentrics busy but is an intrinsic part what makes our universe tic!
His descriptions of the colorful people who laid the foundations of sync were very fun to read.
I will most certainly read his other work based on his lectures!
